Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as a second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after Czechia, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been actively involved in a number of Agency projects over the years.
But Poland's path to space started before.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always understood.
Let me remind you, for example, of A. Sterfeld's lecture, which, on December 6, 1933, represented the idea at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory of its innovative work "Introduction into Space."
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years, Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Hadowski had an interest in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno Peltre Award and André Luis Hirsch for Introduction to Space.
Jan Hadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonauts.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Hadamsky became a well-known world advocate of space, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the other side of the Moon had been named after him.
As early as 1925, Poland had built a rail cutter equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as did the details of the draft.
It is not even clear whether a rocket had to be used for a chase or for braking.
Information about this drift is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to think about missiles.
The study was carried out by the Weapons Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Macheslav Wolfke and Gustav Mokjiskim.
The remaining materials show that the studies have reached the practical test stage.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the specialized press introduced the idea of an electric fighter rocket proposed by an engineer in Rogozinski, and the following year the work of the “Establishment of the carrier missile and the bomb rocket” of the author of Lévalia Khivoloski was launched.
Both projects have been developed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war, all military missile projects had been dealt with by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which had coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, it was completed because of the outbreak of war.
The next work on space science appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, reference is made to society in the November 1954 issue of “Problems”, which contains four voluminous articles on Astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotović proposed to organize a society that would be involved in space.
By then, artificial satellite projects had been gaining momentum, and space research was clearly a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (POA) has tried to join the international Astronautics Federation (based in 1951) and has become a valid member of the Astronautics Federation in the autumn of 1951.
The following year, Kazymed Zarankevich, First President of PAA (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
As such, he remained until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has contributed significantly to the development of the very successful RM meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorogiczna), which was the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first type was launched on 10 October 1958.
A missile capable of reaching a distance of 1,800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved RM-1A version was built and two-step RM-2 rocket testing was conducted in the Bledov Desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already in a position to perform real scientific work -- an RM-34 rocket could have exceeded 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high wind.
In 1962, however, further development was suspended.
The original RM-type missile was inherited by a meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed to be two-tiered, its total length was 510 cm and its initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked as Meteorological-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which were different in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile has a 0.4-litre, a 1-B-0.34-litre-methore-C-0.62-L.
The maximum range for all three types of flight was 37 km.
During the period from 1965 to 1968, the Aviation Institute developed a meteor-2 rocket and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
A 380 kg meteor-2 rocket was able to produce a useful cargo of 10 kg per height of about 60 km.
The version of Meteorological-2N and Meteorological-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ' s accession to COSPAR (the Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of a national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
