Sabo: "The Germans have a more important role to play."
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on U.S. - European relations, Berlin balances on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the voting.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be wary of its special relations with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that the American position does not support either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without speaking too critically towards Israel.
Germany also abstained in the voting on the imposition of the no-fly zone during the March 2011 uprising in Libya.
As a result, NATO has made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The point is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, from the policy that the United States so-called governs to the German foreign policy itself.
The additional complexity of the situation is that Europeans do not have an agreed one-size-fits-all policy.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're only beginning to see their role, but they're on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy by France or Great Britain.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
This is a willingness to adopt a position that is independent of the position of the United States or European partners in its national interest.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. exports and linkages with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The economic interests of Germany are very different from those of other major States, and therefore Germany must protect its own interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It therefore needs to be careful not to offend the public and elites in Arab countries.
Either way, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to this, it's not a completely unilateral connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Has Germany damaged its relationship with the United States by refraining from taking important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even acquire some respect in this way.
It is a sign that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that it should be considered with its interest.
In Europe, there are differing views on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, it was clear that it was in favour of the veto.
Are there differences between the United States and many European States?
Because of American domestic policies, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has an adequate understanding of the European position.
But because of the local political situation, the Government cannot take that position openly.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as large as they always appear.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not pleased with Netanyahu.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of a key partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes this situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, uncontroversial European policy, but this is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot act as part of a broader approach and are forced to act instead based only on their own vision of the situation.
That's how they get off the euro.
I think Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position in the future.
Clearly, this is not easy for Germany, even because of connection with Israel.
The subject was always sensitive.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany saw itself as an important international player, would it not take on a truly central role?
Or is Germany still hard to take the lead?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to this; it is still always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, has always been hard to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis -- every time Germany takes on an important role, a wide range of anti-German feelings manifest themselves.
The Germans don't just deal with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and opinions, and this is not easy.
So the U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at this point the EU is not filling this vacuum, then who is left?
The Germans just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, it makes you feel uncomfortable or unloved, it's life!
Stephen Sabo, Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., Institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly study the problems of the transatlantic community.
